04944nam a22007935i 9780231538633DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014045626  a(OCoLC)979904303  a97802315386337 a10.7312/gols164302doi  a(DE-B1597)458338  a(OCoLC)916952164  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPS323.5b.G65 2015 7aLIT0140002bisacsh04a811/.5092231 aGolston, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPoetic Machinations :bAllegory, Surrealism, and Postmodern Poetic Form /cMichael Golston. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPolemical Preface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Entomologies -- t2. Epistemologies -- t3. A=L=L=E=G=O=R=I=E=S -- t4. Semiologies -- t5. Fictocritical Postlude -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe shape, lineation, and prosody of postmodern poems are extravagantly inventive, imbuing both form and content with meaning. Through a survey of American poetry and poetics from the end of World War II to the present, Michael Golston traces the proliferation of these experiments to a growing fascination with allegory in philosophy, linguistics, critical theory, and aesthetics, introducing new strategies for reading American poetry while embedding its formal innovations within the history of intellectual thought.Beginning with Walter Benjamin's explicit understanding of Surrealism as an allegorical art, Golston defines a distinct engagement with allegory among philosophers, theorists, and critics from 1950 to today. Reading Fredric Jameson, Angus Fletcher, Roland Barthes, and Craig Owens, and working with the semiotics of Charles Sanders Pierce, Golston develops a theory of allegory he then applies to the poems of Louis Zukofsky and Lorine Niedecker, who, he argues, wrote in response to the Surrealists; the poems of John Ashbery and Clark Coolidge, who incorporated formal aspects of filmmaking and photography into their work; the groundbreaking configurations of P. Inman, Lyn Hejinian, Myung Mi Kim, and the Language poets; Susan Howe's "Pierce-Arrow," which he submits to semiotic analysis; and the innovations of Craig Dworkin and the conceptualists. Revitalizing what many consider to be a staid rhetorical trope, Golston positions allegory as a creative catalyst behind American poetry's postwar avant-garde achievements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAllegory. 0aAmerican poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPoetics. 0aSurrealism (Literature) 0aSurrealism (Literature). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aCoolidge, Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHejinian, Lyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowe, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInman, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKim, Myung Mi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNiedecker, Lorine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZukofsky, Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231538633.jpg  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL